segments.text: strictly a poor boy's school then.
Describe the project houses.
Well, the project houses, incidentally, there was one at A&M.
The building is still there where the campus security is.
That was built by the American Eagle.
The money for it and everything, and they sponsored these boys in that building.
The other project houses started by...
mostly by Dan Russell, I believe it was.
They took different counties, and there'd be some lady that would come from those counties, maybe a widow lady or somebody like that, and she would be the cook.
And they'd bring their groceries from that county into that pocket house, and these boys would stay there in that pocket house.
Now did the rest of y'all respect the project house boys?
Did y'all make fun of them as being poor kids?
I remember one time there was a group that they picked up all over the United States and they put in a dormitory there.
I've forgotten the name of the dormitory.
They brought them in and
and put them in that dormitory.
They brought them in from out of Texas and everywhere.
And that was rumored to be a pretty rough place.
However, as I understand it, there were several of them that had lived there where part of it later became real outstanding good people.
And I think George McCullough, George McCullough,
who would later be the dean of the graduate school.
He was one, and Harry Kunkel was one.
I think that the one that ended up running that concession stand at A&M across from the old high school that I went to was one of that dudes.
They were right along by the time I graduated from A&M or something.
I think that's about when they started.
Let's see.
On the campus, what were the major buildings?
Describe the campus when you were a student.
What was there?
Well, as you go on the campus, I remember the Mitchell Hall.
Did you go to him with your hernia?
No.
I don't think they'd take care of that.
I went up there once several times.
We had to pay, when you're registering in, you had to pay some kind of a fee, but you could go on what's called sick call over there.
And they had some bids there.
I remember being there one time with the flu.
They had beds there and nurses, of course.
There used to be a nurse called Mom Clegghorn that was there.
That hospital was right on the other side of the President Hall.
And going down the Military Walk on the left was Mitchell Hall, Legend Hall.
YMCA was out on the right.
remember a gas ride hall and then there was a hall place on further down that as you go to gun hall it was on the left it was a very uh was it was hart hall there yet no it wasn't
This hall was on the left just before you get to God Hall at the end of the military wall.
There was an old red brick building there.
I've seen the pictures.
Real nice architecture.
I remember I would go up in there when I was going to school and get pigeons out of there and take them over inside a

what did y'all what happened at gyne hall what did y'all do at gyne hall well gyne hall is where they had the ceremonies as I remember I don't know if that's where I received my diploma or not did they show movies in gyne hall
No, there was another hall right next to the old, across from the YMCA building was the Hollywood, or what do you call it, tents?
It had the square tent where the students stayed also.
I was there at that time.
I don't know whether I was at college or in or not.
And off to the right of that was where they had the movies.
That was just before you get to the Presley's house.
Facing west of the wide city building.
It had two stories.
Well, sort of like the Army houses.
had a balcony around, and I've forgotten how the seating was, but the seating was according to class.
Seniors had the seats that they wanted, and I remember going to school, I'd have to slip in there, and sometimes the Aggies would pick me up overhead and take me in.
This is when you were in high school?
Well, this is kind of when I was in grade school.
Oh, oh, grade school.
Okay.
Oh, okay.
They didn't check the tickets too close.
But we'd have, oh, incidentally, there, too, we'd go in this hall.
I've forgotten the name of it.
It's kind of where the chapel is now.

with the Aggies were playing out of town in football, they had a black board up there, green, and they would, over the radio I suppose, and they would mark on that board how the football team was doing, and they had that in the hall.
And it had a good attendance.
And let's see, then the academic building was the big building, wasn't it?
The one with the dome on it.
Right, right.
That was the big...
The flagpole out in front of there is the one I'm talking about that quite often when Colonel Andy was in combat, they'd run up a flag and he'd have to pay somebody to climb up there and get it down.
And then Cushing Library...
I don't think it was that.
Really?
I don't really remember.
Now, where did you take most of it?
We had the exchange store.
When I was going to school, that right in front of the exchange store was the grocery store.
On campus?
On campus.
And on the other side of the grocery store was the electrical shop, the plumbing shop, and stuff like that.
Did the whistle blow at 8 o'clock, 12 o'clock?
Oh, yes.
To this day, I still did that at 8 o'clock, at 12 o'clock, 1 o'clock, and then at 5.
And you could hear people out.
You don't realize how people out in the country at that time depended on that whistle.
People several miles away.
Now, the railroad station was a busy place.
Oh, yeah, that's the first track that the ING and I did was.
They had a railroad building there, of course, on the other side of Southern Pacific.
And the trains run pretty well on schedule, several times a day, going between Houston and Dallas.
And I remember we got on one time.
was able to go, we went to, I believe, Baton Rouge at a football game.
And they let us sleep on the train.
And we also, that time that there was a fight up there at Baylor when they suspended up there, I went with my uncle.
Everybody went up on the train and they had a baggage car where they'd have soda water and sandwiches and whatnot.
And I would say the entire group that went to the game went on trains.
Very few people used a car to go.
And we had some indication before we went up there of what they were going to do.
And they had been told to please do not do that.
They were ridiculing the, as I remember, the farmerettes, or the farm girls.
And some old big boy, they had a car that went out on the field, and some old boy went out there and jumped into them.
And they started, they were doing some repair work at Baylor Stadium.
And they had a bunch of boards around there about three feet long, and a bunch of those.
At that time, too, at the football games, all the freshmen came over and sat on the sidelines, freshman football players.
So they had boards, and they got out in the middle of the field and they were fighting, and then they played the Star-Spangled Banner and a lot of Aggies stood at attention.
And one of them was hit.
Hit with a board?
Yes.
Best I remember.
I'm sure that's what it was.
Anyway, that boy died.
And as I understand from later on, Dr. T.O.
Walton, a man that I respected a lot.
He was a good man.
He had time for anybody.
He was a good man.
He told me that if they sent somebody up there for a period of a
maybe three or four years and paid his way at Baylor, but they never really found out who did that.
But they suspended all athletics with
for four years I was schooled or something like that.
Now was this while you were a student or a little earlier?
This was earlier.
My uncle took me up there by train and that was, I couldn't have been over maybe 12 or 13 at the time.
Now when you were a freshman, did you go to any of the out of town football games?
Did you go on a court trip?
Well, I went to the one over there in Louisiana that time.
Don't remember much about it, although we slept on the train.
Oh, I went to Dallas on several occasions, and I knew a girl that I had met.
This is something else.
When I was at, anyway, this girl I had met was going to SMU
And I remember my clothes were rather shabby.
SMU was a moneyed school, and I somewhat felt a little bit out of place.
But I enjoyed myself.
I remember I went on a court trip to SMU up there, and that's when two of the girls from CIA,
They were so often, they'd come down to A&M and go to these dances and whatnot.
And there was a correspondence way that the girls from there would send a letter to the same box number at A&M.
I remember a little bit about that.
Did you ever have a date with one of those, a blind date with a CIA girl?
No, I didn't.
I took a little money, and somehow or another, transportation or something.
As a freshman and sophomore, I didn't have the money to go to those dances.
When you went to that court trip in Dallas, you went on the train.
Where did you spend the night?
I don't really remember whether we spent it on the train or sometimes we'd get a room between a bunch of us together, I suppose.
I remember something about that.
Did the Aggies party much on court trips?
Well, we thought we were, but we didn't drink very much, anything like that.
Once in a while they would a little bit, but drinking wasn't a problem back there.
During those years, did you ever hitchhike?
All the time.
Describe how an Aggie hitchhiked in those days.
Well, you'd go up there more or less to the east, where the East Gate is now, near Walton Drive.
I've seen as many as a hundred or two out there.
going to Houston as an example.
It seemed like every car that had an empty space would stop for us, and of course we took turns.
That is, about when you were there, you had to get back in line.
And a lot of times at that time, the bunch would go to Houston.
I went down there for a ride scheme.
And so many of us were there,
At that time, they were hauling cotton down to Houston, Galveston, cotton trucks, and they were always coming back empty with flatbeds.
And I've been on those flatbeds with those Aggies coming back.
I suppose 40 or 50 on a flatbed, they'd haul us back to College Station.
Do you remember ever hearing of an Aggie having a bad hitchhike experience?
No.
I haven't heard of it.
Do you remember any interesting hitchhike experiences, though?
Funny?
Goofy?
No, I really don't.
I remember several of them from the Army.
I hitchhiked when I got out of the Army.
at Camp Robert.
I was going to OCS and I hitchhiked back.
What about some pranks or jokes or good bull that students did when you were at A&M?
Well, I think there was a regular session of that they called it, a bull session.
I remember one thing what we would do, they would do quite a bit.
They'd get some freshman to come in there, and they'd give him his stripes, you know.
He was really a gung-ho, and they'd give him his stripes, but he'd get them sewed on and everything, but they'd be upside down.
And they would tell him that was so they'd catch water, hold water.
And he'd write his folks and tell them about how he'd been promoted and all that.
And, you know, they'd come to find out that was just a joke on him.
I remember that.
I remember
Well, like for instance in the little tents across from Guyon Hall, I mean not Guyon Hall, the YMCA, we had wood heaters in there.
And we'd get in there once in a while and sit around.
That was more or less our entertainment because
The picture shows didn't maybe just one or two nights a week or something like that.
The rest of the time you either listened to the radio or study or sit around with bull sessions.
Did you all ever play any tricks on any teacher?
Not that I remember.
As you think back, who were the teachers, the advisors that really were important in your A&M days?
Who were the people that were real helpful?
I remember S.S. Morgan was very helpful for me.
There was another teacher in college algebra that helped me real well, and I remember Mr. Powell.
in the cotton market in the classes that I took.
I enjoyed that, and I thought he was very able, and I enjoyed the classes, got a lot out of it.
And this Morgan was an English teacher,
Did you all have a nickname for him?
Later they would call him Bloody Morgan because there would be so much red ink on your term paper it would be like he had spilled blood on it.
I don't remember that.
I remember Mr. Snuggs, he'd get out in class when you first came there and he said, my name is, I believe, Professor Snuggs.
And he said, I'm married to Mrs. Snuggs, and we live in our snuggie little home.
You ever heard that?
No.
That's good.
That's good.
I remember that to this day.
All right.
What about over in agriculture?
Were there some important people and good teachers over there?
Well, I can't recall some of the names.
I remember I had one.
I'll try to think of his name, one teacher in agronomy.
I can't say that I disliked him, because that wouldn't be fair to him.
But I took agronomy 105.
It was a five-hour course, and I was also working at the time, and I didn't spend the time studying.
It was a very difficult course.
He had a bunch of us in there, and to this day I wish I had learned more in that course.
I can't say that I blame him for it.
Was Dean Kyle still around in those days?
Yes.
Please describe him.
I haven't had anybody talk about him before.
What was he like?
I always thought he was a little aloof.
He was the Dean of Agriculture, as I remember.
And there was something there, a little something about naming Kyle Field.
I asked Pinky Downs one time about it, and Pinky Downs said he didn't want to talk about it.
So that's about all I really know about it.
I do know that Dean Kyle's brother, the best to operate on me for a hernia, when I was in my,
Between my second sophomore year and junior year, I went to Houston and had a hernia operation.
And it was Dean Kyle's brother that did the surgery?
He operated on me at Jefferson Davis Hospital down there in Houston.
That was Dean Kyle's brother.
What did Dean Kyle look like?
As I remember, he was kind of a tall, aloof, just kind of held himself off.
Of course, he was the dean of agriculture.
you realize, too, that he was the one that would put the final say on whether you stayed in school or not.
My grades weren't too good.
I was a little between not being able to go back and see friends.
Now, was Walton the president then?
Who was president?
I don't remember.
I knew Dr. Walton really later, real well, when he became postmaster at College Station.
Describe his personality.
Well, he had time for anybody.
He'd come down and he had a very good understanding.
if someone had a problem there, the post office is an example, we'd call them in his office, sit them down, and talk to them.
I remember one occasion when the student was very unhappy, came in there, and Dr. Walton said, now young man, he said, I want you to get up and leave, and when you
know how to act, respect me, well then you come back.
Sure enough, the young man went back later and apologized to him.
That's the only time I've ever known him to be a... You were talking about Dr. Walton.
What was he physically?
Was he big, small?
Yeah, he was a pretty good sized person.
Really was.
But like I say, he had time to talk to each and any individual about various, any subject.
He wasn't, sometimes way back there particularly, some of the professors

you didn't feel like relaxed with him that it is but dr walton's college person that you uh he was interested he let everybody know that he was interested in what they had to say and we'll talk to him very much uh mr uh cashin describe him
He was in charge at YMCA, I remember.
There was a Mr.
Gay there, too.
Gordon Gay.
And we used to go there as, when I was in, before I was in A&M, and we would play checkers and dominoes.
And they also had ping pong tables.
They were very nice.
They treated us okay.
Sometimes I think you got tired of us kids coming in there.
See, that was a place where the campus kids and off-campus kids could associate together in the old YMCA building.
And they had newspapers and magazines in there, and go downstairs and maybe get a banana split from Casey's.
And they had a swimming pool there, and kids from Bryan used to come out to that swimming pool.
Sometimes I think certain days you had to wear a bathing suit, but sometimes you didn't have to wear a bathing suit.
And some of the girls from around there would use that swimming pool.
It was down in the basement next to where they had the pool tables.
Did you know either of the Little Cashin' Boys at that time, Red or Jim?
No, I think
I remember when Red Cashion was quarterbacking for A&M a little bit, but not too well.
Let's see.
Let's go back to football.
Describe what you and your buddies, when you were an A&M student, describe a football home game day.
What time did y'all start doing things when there was a home football game?
What did you do?
Well, it really, at that time, I did the best I could.
It wasn't that big an occasion when I was going to A&M.
Did y'all march into the stadium?
I've forgotten.
But you did stand up.
Oh, yes.
And if the Aggies won, what did y'all do to the L leaders?
Did you take them to the fish pond?
I don't remember for sure.
When I was going to school, I really don't remember that.
Now, let's see.
Was Coach Bible still here or Homer Norton here when you were a student?
That was back in 1938.
That would be Coach Norton then.
Dick Todd?
Would have been one of the star players.
I remember Dick Todd was playing when I was going to school.
Maybe they got him somewhere.
Did the athletes get pampered then?
Did the athletes have special courses?
No.
They were just like everybody else?
They were just like everybody else.
As a matter of fact, they stayed in the dormitories with all the rest of the students.
That is, the professors might have looked at, gave them a little bit of special attention, but I don't think so.
They were just mingled in with all the students.
It wasn't until later on that they separated them.
And were there some notable students then?
Was there anybody here whose father was governor or senator or rich person?
Not that I remember.
Give some examples of how financially tough it was.
Well, as an example, my stepdad came in with either a week's salary or a two-week salary and gave me that.
I don't know whether he had any left over or not for me to register for A&M.
Did you have any spending money as the years went along?
No.
Even when I was going to A&M,
I didn't get banana splits down at Mr. Casey's.
That was just on occasion.
They were 25 cents.
Did you work while you were an Aggie?
Yes.
I had a hard time getting a job at the time, 25 cents an hour.
I finally did get on with it.
landscape department, I suppose is what you'd call that, at 25th Street.
We did the mowed grass, did various things around on the campus like that.
And also, they took care of the stables.
There were some stables there, well, more or less where Olsen Field is now.
They had some Army people there.
It was a two-story building.
and I don't know how many people there, and they took care of the horses for the artillery, and they took care of various things, and also they taught some classes.
Oh, I took one of the classes, signal corps, and that was taught by one of the sergeants of that group, but they also had these stables
at the University or the college taking care of the horses.
And I worked, working in the stables was the preferred job for it, I was concerned, because you got out of the sun and in the stables, even though you had to do some sweeping and you got
